The `document.addEventListener(...)` method takes a function as the second argument.
You could wrap the `console.log` in a function:

    document.addEventListener(&#39;keydown&#39;, function() { console.log(&quot;test&quot;); });

or declare a separate function and call that:


    function LogIt(ev) {
      console.log(&quot;test&quot;);
    }
    
    document.addEventListener(&#39;keydown&#39;, LogIt);

You can reference
https://www.w3schools.com/jsref/met_document_addeventlistener.asp

There is a relatively new operator that is being suggested. Arrow Functions.
Similar to a delegate in C#. However, you may want to review browser compatibility if using this in a production environment. If just learning, no worries!
https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/Arrow_functions

